Great question! This is where Claude really shines — you can wire multiple MCPs together into a single conversational automation hub. Let me show you the full picture.
First, the architecture of how multiple MCPs connect through Claude:

The key mental model: Claude is the brain, MCPs are the hands. You write one natural language request and Claude decides which tools to call, in what order, then synthesises everything into one output.
Now here are the three most powerful automation patterns you can build with your exact stack:
Pattern 1 — PR-to-production pipeline assistant
One prompt triggers a chain across 4 MCPs:
I've just merged PR #482 to order-service. 
Do the following:

1. [GitHub MCP] Get the PR diff and list all changed files
2. [Jira MCP] Find the ticket linked in the PR description, 
   update its status to "In Review" and add a comment with 
   the PR link
3. [Harness MCP] Trigger the order-service staging pipeline 
   and return the pipeline execution URL
4. [Confluence MCP] Find the deployment runbook for order-service 
   and summarise the post-deploy verification steps I need to run

Return everything as a structured deployment checklist.
Claude calls each MCP in sequence, waits for results, and gives you a single checklist. No tab-switching.
Pattern 2 — sprint kickoff automation
Every Monday morning, one prompt generates the full sprint brief:
Sprint planning for team: backend-platform, sprint 47.

1. [Jira MCP] Get all tickets in the sprint backlog tagged 
   "backend-platform", sorted by priority
2. [GitHub MCP] For each ticket with a linked PR, check if 
   the PR is still open or needs review
3. [Confluence MCP] Pull last sprint's retrospective page 
   and extract the "action items" section
4. [Splunk MCP] Get last week's error rate summary for 
   order-service, payment-service, and inventory-service

Generate a sprint brief with:
- Ticket list with owners and estimates
- PRs needing attention
- Carry-over actions from last retro
- Service health context
Pattern 3 — test failure → full context report (HyperExecute + GitHub + Jira)
When a HyperExecute test run fails:
HyperExecute job ID: HE-20450 has failures.

1. [Harness/HyperExecute MCP] Get the failed test names, 
   error messages, and affected modules from job HE-20450
2. [GitHub MCP] Search the codebase for the failing test 
   class names and find the last commit that touched those files
3. [Jira MCP] Check if there's an open bug for any of these 
   test failures already — search by test class name
4. For failures with no existing Jira ticket, create a new 
   bug ticket with: failing test, error message, suspect commit, 
   and assigned to the committer

Return a summary of failures, existing tickets found, 
and new tickets created.
How to actually build this: 3 approaches
Approach A — Claude.ai with MCPs enabled (what you're doing now) Lowest setup effort. Connect all MCPs in Claude settings, then write multi-step prompts like above. Best for: ad-hoc automation, individual engineer workflows. Limitation: manual trigger only.
Approach B — Claude API + MCP SDK in a custom app Build a small internal web app or Slack bot. Engineers type /deploy PR-482 and it fires the multi-MCP chain behind the scenes. The Claude API with tool-use handles the orchestration — each MCP becomes a tool definition you pass in. Best for: team-wide automation with a clean UI.
Approach C — Claude Code (agentic CLI) Use Claude Code for automation that lives in your repo. Write a deploy-assist.md prompt file, run claude -p deploy-assist.md in CI, and it can read files, call APIs, and write outputs — all from the terminal or pipeline. Best for: CI-embedded automation (e.g., auto-generate release notes from GitHub + Jira on every merge).
The most important design rule
When chaining MCPs, always tell Claude the shape of output you want upfront. Instead of "check Jira and GitHub", say "check Jira and GitHub, then return a markdown table with columns: ticket, status, PR, reviewer". Claude will structure every intermediate step to feed into that final shape, rather than dumping raw tool output.
